<m0>   Attention, fans of Camelot.<ep>
   Just days after the last auctioneer's gavel fell in the Jackie O estate auction, you are about to get a chance to eyeball an entirely different lot of Kennedy goods on television.<ep>
   Dominick Dunne's best-seller <m0>Season in Purgatory,  <m0>a CBS miniseries airing Sunday and Tuesday, is an unabashed study of the Kennedy family pathology.<ep>
   It's officially about the fictional Bradley family, a wealthy political brood caught in a murder and its cover-up, but Dunne draws such close parallels with the real-life Kennedy dynasty that even the Hyannis Port scullery maids will be able to recognize themselves. The family itself is a cross-hatched composite of three generations of Kennedys (--) saintly matriarch, dysfunctional children, womanizing menfolk and all.<ep>
   At its center is Gerald Bradley, a Joe Kennedy-like patriarch played by Brian Dennehy, himself a dead ringer for Ted Kennedy. Gerald is married to Grace. With a name like that, she's meant to be the Rose character, but (--) in an oddly funny twist (--) she's played by Blair Brown, the actress born to wear a pillbox hat. Like Rose and Joe's and Jack and Jackie's, theirs is a marriage of double standards. She's an avid Mass-goer; he goes after his daughters' friends.<ep>
    Their children, too, are a fictional mishmash of JFK's siblings and his nieces and nephews (--) handsome, athletic youngsters whose mishaps <m2><ql>
