<m0>and felonies alike are swept under the rug by Daddy's influence. (As daughter Kitt, Sherilyn Fenn of <m0>Twin Peaks <m0> fame chews scenery as the family lush.)<ep>
   Set at the Bradleys' beach house, Manhattan apartments and sprawling Connecticut mansion, the miniseries is a voyeur's dream, a video skeleton-key that's lets us into the corridors of money and elitism that until now we've only been able to read about. And what a strange Irish universe it is: There's no one in it without a brogue or a freckle. In one scene, Grace casually rechristens a maid (--) changing her name from Debbie to Colleen (--) as though it were the charitable thing to do.<ep>
   Idiosyncrasies aside, the central story's about a murder committed by Constant, the favorite son and presidential fodder, and the way the family covers it up by manipulating Constant's shanty-Irish schoolmate Harry (Patrick Dempsey), a scholarship boy who is befriended by the Bradleys because of his book smarts. <m1> <m0>The crime, a date-rape gone to extremes, contains elements of the two most famous Kennedy legal brouhahas, Chappaquiddick and the more recent William Kennedy Smith rape trial.<ep>
   It's been years since the gleam of Camelot started to tarnish, but it's still wildly refreshing to have the Kennedy excesses, however thinly disguised, laid out for our inspection. Through Gerald and his sons, we see a dynasty supposedly built on pro-family blarney that's actually fueled by the ability to buy or intimidate anyone. As one character puts it, ``The Bradleys aren't just a family. They're a religion, a cult.'' <ep>
   <m0>Season of Purgatory  <m0>doesn't so much point the finger as yank the cloth off the altar on which we've placed the Kennedys. <ep>
   That's why the best parts of the miniseries aren't the scenes about Gerald's iron-fisted powermongering or Harrison's soul-searching about exposing the crime (--) or even the devilish cliffhanger that concludes part one. Instead, it's the scenes of incidents we always suspected happened behind closed doors.<ep>
   Like when Bonnie Bedelia (who gives the series' best performance), cast as the gritty lawyer defending Constant, shocks the Kennedy women by using a sexual term that wouldn't turn the head of a fifth-grader. Or when, minutes after Gerald suffers a stroke, Grace goes to her room to try on funeral veils, only to be told her husband's going to live. <ep>
   What to make of all this? When networks trot out miniseries that delve into leadership qualities, it can only mean the presidential election is a few months off. Watch <m0>Season of Purgatory  <m0>and remember, we get the idols we deserve.<ql>
